Indian Equities: Coal India, Pipavav Shipyard, State Bank

-- B y   H e m a l   S a v a i
-- 
2011-09-06T04:42:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-06/indian-equities-coal-india-pipavav-shipyard-state-bank.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 9:28 a.m. local time.  India ’s Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex,
lost 56.36, or 0.3 percent, to 16,656.97. The BSE200 Index fell
0.2 percent to 2,069.26.  Banks:  State Bank of India (SBIN)  , the nation’s largest
lender, dropped 1 percent to 1,986.2 rupees while  ICICI Bank
Ltd. (ICICIBC)  , the second-largest, slid 1.2 percent to 872.5
rupees. The stocks had their ratings lowered by Macquarie Group
Ltd. analysts Suresh Ganapathy and Mudit Painuly, who said
balance sheets of banks and financial companies are becoming
less transparent and non-performing loans are rising.  The brokerage cut  State Bank  to “underperform” with a
price estimate of 1,700 rupees. ICICI Bank was reduced to
“neutral” with a price estimate of 920 rupees.  Coal India Ltd. (COAL)   declined 1.2 percent to 376.55
rupees, headed for its lowest close in a week. The state-owned
company cut its output target for the year ending March 2017 by
16 percent to 556.4 million metric tons because of delays in
environmental approvals and land acquisitions, Coal Minister
Sriprakash Jaiswal said.  Pipavav Shipyard Ltd. (PIPV)  , the largest shipbuilder by
market value, advanced 1.1 percent to 77.45 rupees, on course
for its highest close in two months after the Business Standard
reported that Indian billionaire investor Rakesh Jhunjhunwala
may buy a stake. Two calls made to Pipavav Chairman Nikhil
Gandhi’s mobile phone weren’t answered.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Hemal Savai in Mumbai at  at
 hsavai@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 